1. Project Overview
In an operating system, page replacement algorithms are used to manage memory efficiently when a page fault occurs and the physical memory frames are full. The operating system must decide which page to remove from memory to make space for a new page.
This project, Page Replacement Algorithm Simulator, is a console-based simulation written in C that demonstrates the working of three fundamental page replacement algorithms:
•	First-In First-Out (FIFO)
•	Least Recently Used (LRU)
•	Optimal Page Replacement
The simulator allows the user to input:
•	Number of page references
•	Reference string
•	Number of memory frames
The program then simulates each algorithm step-by-step, displaying HIT / FAULT status and the current frame contents, and finally compares the total page faults produced by each algorithm.
Key Outcomes
•	Understand page replacement strategies
•	Compare algorithm efficiency
•	Analyze page fault behavior
•	Visualize memory frame changes
